04497nam a22005415i 9780226144955DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013050783  a9780226144955  a(DE-B1597)568129  a(OCoLC)1233040966  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aDT397.3b.B475 2014 4aDT397.3b.B475 2014 7aSOC0000002bisacsh  aLB 42000qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90551:7721 aBernal, Victoria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNation as Network :bDiaspora, Cyberspace, and Citizenship /cVictoria Bernal. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Nations, Migration, and the World Wide Web of Politics -- t1. Infopolitics and Sacrificial Citizenship: Sovereignty in Spaces Beyond the Nation -- t2. Diasporic Citizenship and the Public Sphere: Creating National Space Online -- t3. The Mouse that Roars: Websites as an Off shore Platform for Civil Society -- t4. Mourning Becomes Electronic: Representing the Nation in a Virtual War Memorial -- t5. Sex, Lies, and Cyberspace: Political Participation and the “Woman Question” -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow is the internet transforming the relationships between citizens and states? What happens to politics when international migration is coupled with digital media, making it easy for people to be politically active in a nation from outside its borders? In Nation as Network, Victoria Bernal creatively combines media studies, ethnography, and African studies to explore this new political paradigm through a striking analysis of how Eritreans in diaspora have used the internet to shape the course of Eritrean history. Bernal argues that Benedict Anderson’s famous concept of nations as “imagined communities” must now be rethought because diasporas and information technologies have transformed the ways nations are sustained and challenged. She traces the development of Eritrean diaspora websites over two turbulent decades that saw the Eritrean state grow ever more tyrannical. Through Eritreans’ own words in posts and debates, she reveals how new subjectivities are formed and political action is galvanized online. She suggests that “infopolitics”—struggles over the management of information—make politics in the 21st century distinct, and she analyzes the innovative ways Eritreans deploy the internet to support and subvert state power. Nation as Network is a unique and compelling work that advances our understanding of the political significance of digital media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCyberspacexSocial aspects. 0aEritreansxPolitical activity. 0aInternet and activism. 0aInternet and immigrants. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ainternet, citizens, state power, migration, international, digital media, nation, activism, political engagement, ethnography, african studies, eritreans, diaspora, belonging, displacement, imagined communities, infopolitics, emigration, immigration, cyberspace, citizenship, war memorial, virtual, websites, offshore, public sphere, sovereignty, nonfiction, history, government, politics, sociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226144955423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226144955/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles